  potentialHarmsIdentified: "1. False negatives in trade surveillance — missed suspicious activity could result in regulatory sanctions\n2. False positives — excessive alerts causing alert fatigue and operational burden\n3. Model drift — degraded performance over time as market conditions change\n4. Over-reliance on AI — reduced human analytical capability if staff defer to model outputs\n5. Data leakage — theoretical risk of training data memorization exposing sensitive patterns",
  harmMitigationMeasures: "1. Human-in-the-loop review required for all surveillance alerts before regulatory reporting\n2. Alert threshold tuning during onboarding to optimize precision/recall balance for firm's risk appetite\n3. Monthly model drift monitoring with automatic alerts at configurable degradation thresholds\n4. AI output presented as recommendations with confidence scores, not automated decisions\n5. Differential privacy techniques applied during model fine-tuning to prevent data memorization\n6. Quarterly model validation review by firm's Model Risk Management team per SR 11-7",
